{
  "id": "sample-book-001",
  "title": "The Detective's Apprentice",
  "author": "Hermes AI",
  "subtitle": "A Mystery Novel",
  "parts": [],
  "chapters": [
    {"id": "ch-01", "title": "Chapter 1: The Missing Heiress", "order": 0, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3000, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-01-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Phone Call", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Phone Call</h2><p>The rain hammered against the windows of Detective Sarah Mitchell's office. It was 3 AM. \"Mitchell.\" \"Detective, this is Captain Reeves. We have a situation. Fairview Hotel. A young woman has vanished.\" \"Who's the victim?\" \"Diane Ashworth. Daughter of Richard Ashworth.\" \"I'm on my way.\"", "wordCount": 312}, {"id": "sc-01-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Fairview Hotel", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Fairview Hotel</h2><p>Room 412. The window was open. On the pillow — a single red rose. On the nightstand — a note: \"Meet me at the old pier. Come alone. —J\" In the bathroom mirror, written in lipstick: \"SHE'S MINE NOW\"", "wordCount": 589}, {"id": "sc-01-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Drive Back", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Drive Back</h2><p>Sarah drove to the old pier. Halfway down — another rose, another note: \"You're getting closer, Detective. But the truth is darker than you think.\" Someone was leading her. Every rose, every note — breadcrumbs.", "wordCount": 498}, {"id": "sc-01-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Research", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Research</h2><p>Black Baccara roses. A brass skeleton key with 412 on the ribbon. Three nurseries matched the fertilizer. She pocketed the key and headed for the door.", "wordCount": 612}]},
    {"id": "ch-02", "title": "Chapter 2: The Old Pier", "order": 1, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-02-01", "title": "Scene 1: Arrival at the Pier", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: Arrival at the Pier</h2><p>A rose, a note, a brass key with 412 on the ribbon. Room 412. But the key was too old for a hotel. Someone was watching her.", "wordCount": 621}, {"id": "sc-02-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Station", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Station</h2><p>\"Diane was investigating her father. Forty-seven million in embezzlement.\" The Ashworth Home for Girls — closed in 2003 after abuse allegations. Three girls dead. Both investigations shut down.", "wordCount": 931}, {"id": "sc-02-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Accountant", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Accountant</h2><p>Lisa Chen: \"Diane was going to the FBI. She had a contact — someone she called J.\"", "wordCount": 872}]},
    {"id": "ch-03", "title": "Chapter 3: The Lighthouse Keeper", "order": 2, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-03-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Morning After", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Morning After</h2><p>A lighthouse on a cliff. Black Baccara roses in the garden. The door was unlocked.", "wordCount": 598}, {"id": "sc-03-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Keeper", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Keeper</h2><p>\"My name is Arthur Voss. I've been waiting for someone like you.\" Fourteen disappearances. Eleven years of being ignored.", "wordCount": 726}, {"id": "sc-03-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Pattern", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Pattern</h2><p>All fourteen women connected to one institution. \"Claire was my niece. She had a cat named Biscuit. Then she was gone.\"", "wordCount": 738}, {"id": "sc-03-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Box", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Box</h2><p>A metal box buried in the garden. A photograph of the Ashworth Home's board. \"They know what they did. So I will answer for them.\"", "wordCount": 849}]},
    {"id": "ch-04", "title": "Chapter 4: The Photograph", "order": 3, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-04-01", "title": "Scene 1: Back at the Station", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: Back at the Station</h2><p>Margaret Ashworth — Richard's mother — was on the board from 1985 to 2003. The Ashworths had been burying problems for generations.", "wordCount": 598}, {"id": "sc-04-02", "title": "Scene 2: Identification", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: Identification</h2><p>\"The Ashworth Home for Girls. Electrical service restored eight months ago. Applied for by A. Voss.\"", "wordCount": 521}, {"id": "sc-04-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Interrogation", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Interrogation</h2><p>\"I buried the key because I wanted someone to find it.\" Voss admitted to orchestrating the trail. But Diane's disappearance? \"Richard Ashworth is behind it.\"", "wordCount": 892}, {"id": "sc-04-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Decision", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Decision</h2><p>Reeves handed Sarah the master key. \"Find her.\"", "wordCount": 678}]},
    {"id": "ch-05", "title": "Chapter 5: Room 412", "order": 4, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-05-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Ashworth Home", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Ashworth Home</h2><p>Red brick and rust. Someone had been using it recently. Up the stairs. East wing. Room 412 — a metal door.", "wordCount": 628}, {"id": "sc-05-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Room", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Room</h2><p>Someone had been living here. Walls covered in photographs and red string. Surveillance photos of Sarah. A fresh rose outside the door.", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-05-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Confrontation", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Confrontation</h2><p>A metal box under the cot. A USB drive and a letter from J. \"Diane is alive. Richard knows you're investigating.\"", "wordCount": 812}, {"id": "sc-05-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Evidence", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Evidence</h2><p>\"Hundreds of millions. Richard's signature is on half these documents.\" J called. \"Diane is at a cabin off Route 9.\"", "wordCount": 967}]},
    {"id": "ch-06", "title": "Chapter 6: The Cabin", "order": 5, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-06-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Choice", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Choice</h2><p>\"You're going after Diane. Alone. Bring her back alive.\"", "wordCount": 834}, {"id": "sc-06-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Cabin", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Cabin</h2><p>Diane was alive. J was Julia Voss — Arthur's niece. \"I saved Diane. I've been collecting evidence for fifteen years. I manipulated you. And I'd do it again.\"", "wordCount": 1067}]},
    {"id": "ch-07", "title": "Chapter 7: The Reckoning", "order": 6, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-07-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Ashworth Home", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Ashworth Home</h2><p>Claire Dunbar's death certificate: \"She was murdered. They all were.\" Dozens of photographs labeled Remember.", "wordCount": 721}, {"id": "sc-07-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Arrest", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Arrest</h2><p>Richard Ashworth in handcuffs. \"Everything I've done has been legal.\" \"A system that let you silence fourteen women.\"", "wordCount": 648}, {"id": "sc-07-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Interview", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Interview</h2><p>\"My mother's cousin was Claire Dunbar. My mother died of not knowing. I've spent fifteen years making sure someone would care.\"", "wordCount": 798}, {"id": "sc-07-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Truth", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Truth</h2><p>Sarah at the pier at 3 AM. The truth was out. The trail of roses had ended. The truth had won.", "wordCount": 678}]},
    {"id": "ch-08", "title": "Chapter 8: The Morning After", "order": 7, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-08-01", "title": "Scene 1: Headlines", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: Headlines</h2><p>RICHARD ASHWORTH ARRESTED. \"The case isn't finished. Fourteen women are still unaccounted for.\"", "wordCount": 698}, {"id": "sc-08-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Survivors", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Survivors</h2><p>23 former residents. 14 dead or missing. 9 still alive.", "wordCount": 534}, {"id": "sc-08-03", "title": "Scene 3: Helen Marsh", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: Helen Marsh</h2><p>\"Room 412 wasn't discipline. It was punishment. Girls who talked to investigators disappeared.\"", "wordCount": 712}, {"id": "sc-08-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Pattern", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Pattern</h2><p>All 14 women worked at the home after aging out. All disappeared within 5 years. Catherine Voss called. \"My grandmother hid something.\"", "wordCount": 689}]},
    {"id": "ch-09", "title": "Chapter 9: The Diary", "order": 8, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-09-01", "title": "Scene 1: Catherine's House", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: Catherine's House</h2><p>Margaret Voss's journal. \"I have become complicit in something I cannot stop. This is my confession.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-09-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Director's Confession", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Director's Confession</h2><p>Margaret documented everything — the abuse, the deaths, the bribes. \"Richard knows. He's always known. The home was his idea.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-09-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Second Property", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Second Property</h2><p>\"Girls who couldn't be corrected were sent to the farm.\" Seven properties owned by the Ashworth Trust. One was a farm — forty acres, no records since 1998.", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-09-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Warrant", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Warrant</h2><p>The judge read Margaret's journal. \"This is the most disturbing thing I've read in thirty years. You have your warrant.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-10", "title": "Chapter 10: The Farm", "order": 9, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-10-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Property", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Property</h2><p>Forty acres of weeds. Ground-penetrating radar showed anomalies. \"This is where it ends.\"", "wordCount": 512}, {"id": "sc-10-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Dig", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Dig</h2><p>Nine bodies found on the first day. The rose garden marked the graves. \"There are more — at least five additional anomalies.\"", "wordCount": 587}, {"id": "sc-10-03", "title": "Scene 3: Identification", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: Identification</h2><p>Claire Dunbar. Susan Chen. Rebecca Okafor. Margaret Voss. Each name was a person. Each person was a story.", "wordCount": 623}, {"id": "sc-10-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Fifteenth", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Fifteenth</h2><p>A 15th body. Not on Margaret's list. Dental records: Sarah Ashworth. Richard's sister. Disappeared 1983. Blunt force trauma.", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-11", "title": "Chapter 11: The Sister", "order": 10, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-11-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Photograph", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Photograph</h2><p>Fifteen bodies. Fourteen on Margaret's list. One unknown — Sarah Ashworth, Richard's sister, disappeared 1983. The same captain who shut down the 1996 investigation had suspended her missing persons case.", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-11-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Interrogation", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Interrogation</h2><p>\"She was a liability. She found out what the home was really for. She threatened to go to the police. I couldn't allow that.\" \"You killed her.\" \"I protected my family.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-11-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Deal", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Deal</h2><p>\"He'll plead guilty to all charges — twenty-three counts of murder — in exchange for life without parole. He says there are eight more bodies. On a different property.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-11-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Map", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Map</h2><p>Richard drew a map. A lake, three hours north. \"Girls who couldn't be corrected at the farm were sent there. Weighted and dropped in the deep water. The lake is two hundred feet deep.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-12", "title": "Chapter 12: The Lake", "order": 11, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-12-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Property", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Property</h2><p>The lake was pristine — crystal clear water surrounded by pine forest. Two hundred feet deep. The perfect place to hide a secret.", "wordCount": 512}, {"id": "sc-12-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Dive", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Dive</h2><p>Seven bodies found in the first week. \"She was alive when she went into the water,\" the forensic anthropologist said. \"Defensive wounds on the arms.\"", "wordCount": 587}, {"id": "sc-12-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Eighth", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Eighth</h2><p>Maria Santos. Twenty-two years old. Disappeared 1998. Sarah called her mother. \"We found her.\"", "wordCount": 623}, {"id": "sc-12-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Reckoning", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Reckoning</h2><p>Twenty-three bodies. Richard pleaded guilty to twenty-three counts of murder. Life without parole. \"Thank you for not giving up,\" Arthur Voss said. \"For making them remember.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-13", "title": "Chapter 13: Julia's Trial", "order": 12, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-13-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Arraignment", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Arraignment</h2><p>\"Guilty, Your Honor. I kidnapped Diane Ashworth. I manipulated a police investigation. I did it to save a life.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-13-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Testimony", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Testimony</h2><p>\"I tried the proper channels. Three times. The system was designed to protect the Ashworths. So I found another way.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-13-03", "title": "Scene 3: Sarah Speaks", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: Sarah Speaks</h2><p>\"Julia Voss spent fifteen years trying to get someone to care. When the system failed her, she found another way. Was it legal? No. Was it right? I think history will judge that it was.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-13-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Sentence", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Sentence</h2><p>\"You broke the law. But you also saved a life and exposed a conspiracy buried for sixty years. The system needs people like you to remind it.\" Three years, parole eligible after eighteen months.", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-14", "title": "Chapter 14: The Aftermath", "order": 13, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-14-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Funeral", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Funeral</h2><p>Claire Dunbar's funeral. Thirty survivors. Thirty roses. \"Her death wasn't the end. It was the beginning.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-14-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Foundation", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Foundation</h2><p>Diane started the Ashworth Home Survivors Fund. Two million dollars in the first year. Three new investigations. Legislative reform.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-14-03", "title": "Scene 3: Arthur's Peace", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: Arthur's Peace</h2><p>\"I'm selling the lighthouse. Moving closer to Claire's grave.\" He gave Sarah a Black Baccara. \"So you don't forget.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-14-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Promotion", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Promotion</h2><p>Lieutenant. Head of the Cold Case Unit. \"I'll take it. On one condition. I pick my own team.\" A new text: \"My sister disappeared in 2003. Can you help?\" \"Tell me everything.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-15", "title": "Chapter 15: The Last Rose", "order": 14, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-15-01", "title": "Scene 1: One Year Later", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: One Year Later</h2><p>Fifteen open cases. Fifteen families waiting. \"We're not going to stop until we have answers.\" A DNA hit — a missing sister found alive in Oregon.", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-15-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Reunion", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Reunion</h2><p>\"Elena? She's alive?\" Sarah listened to two sisters cry. Twelve years of grief and hope in a single conversation.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-15-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Garden", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Garden</h2><p>Sarah planted a \"Remembrance\" rose at the lighthouse. \"For all the ones we found. And all the ones we're still looking for.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-15-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Last Rose", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Last Rose</h2><p>A Black Baccara on her desk. \"The trail of roses has ended. But the trail of truth goes on. — J\" Another text. Another family. \"Tell me everything.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-16", "title": "Chapter 16: The Cold Case Unit", "order": 15, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-16-01", "title": "Scene 1: New Beginnings", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: New Beginnings</h2><p>Six months into leading the Cold Case Unit, Sarah had built something that mattered. A team of five detectives, two analysts, and a dedicated prosecutor. They'd solved eight cases. Eight families given answers. But the backlog was enormous — over two hundred cold cases in the county alone.</p><p>\"We can't solve them all,\" Park said, looking at the board.</p><p>\"No,\" Sarah agreed. \"But we can solve the ones in front of us. One at a time. One family at a time.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-16-02", "title": "Scene 2: The File", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The File</h2><p>A new case landed on her desk. A boy, missing since 1995. Fifteen years old. The file was thin — a single detective had worked it for three months before it went cold.</p><p>Sarah read it twice. Something bothered her. The boy had been last seen near the harbor. The same harbor where she'd found the second rose.</p><p>\"Park, pull everything we have on missing persons near the harbor between 1990 and 2000.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-16-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Pattern", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Pattern</h2><p>Park found seventeen cases. Seventeen people who'd disappeared near the harbor over ten years. All different ages. All different backgrounds. But all last seen within a mile of the old pier.</p><p>\"This isn't random,\" Sarah said. \"Someone was working this area. For years.\"</p><p>She thought about Richard Ashworth. About the farm. About the lake. About the girls who'd been taken and never found.</p><p>\"What if the Ashworth Home wasn't the only operation?\" she said. \"What if there was something else? Something we missed?\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-16-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Connection", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Connection</h2><p>Sarah spent the night cross-referencing. The seventeen harbor disappearances. The twenty-three Ashworth victims. The timeline. The geography.</p><p>And then she found it. A name that appeared in both lists. A social worker named David Chen. He'd worked at the Ashworth Home from 1988 to 1995. And he'd been the last person to see three of the harbor victims before they disappeared.</p><p>\"Park,\" she said. \"Find David Chen. Now.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-17", "title": "Chapter 17: The Social Worker", "order": 16, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-17-01", "title": "Scene 1: David Chen", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: David Chen</h2><p>David Chen was fifty-eight years old, living in a suburb two hours south. He'd left social work in 1995 and become a high school counselor. By all accounts, he was well-liked. Respected. A model citizen.</p><p>Sarah and Torres drove down on a Tuesday morning. Chen answered the door in a cardigan and reading glasses, holding a cup of tea.</p><p>\"Mr. Chen, I'm Detective Mitchell. This is Detective Torres. We'd like to ask you some questions about your time at the Ashworth Home.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-17-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Interview", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Interview</h2><p>Chen was cooperative. Too cooperative. He answered every question smoothly, without hesitation. He'd worked at the home for seven years. He'd known about the abuse. He'd reported it to his supervisor. Nothing had been done.</p><p>\"And after you left?\" Sarah asked.</p><p>\"I left social work entirely. I couldn't be part of a system that failed children.\"</p><p>\"Three people who disappeared near the harbor were your clients. All in the year after you left the home.\"</p><p>Chen's expression didn't change. \"I'm sorry to hear that. But I left the area in 1995. I don't know anything about harbor disappearances.\"</p><p>But Sarah noticed something. His left hand. It was trembling. Just slightly. Just enough.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-17-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Search", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Search</h2><p>Sarah got a warrant. They searched Chen's house. Nothing in the main rooms. Nothing in the garage. But in the basement, behind a false wall, they found a room.</p><p>It was small. Concrete. A single chair. A table. And on the table — a journal. Not unlike Margaret Voss's. But this one was different. This one wasn't a confession. It was a record.</p><p>Names. Dates. Locations. Seventeen people. Seventeen disappearances. All documented in meticulous detail.</p><p>Sarah called Reeves. \"We found him. And we found the proof.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-17-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Arrest", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Arrest</h2><p>David Chen didn't run. He was sitting at his kitchen table when they came back, still holding his tea.</p><p>\"You found the room,\" he said. Not a question.</p><p>\"Why?\" Sarah asked. \"You were a social worker. You were supposed to protect them.\"</p><p>\"I did protect them. From the Ashworths. From room 412. From the farm. I got them out. And then I gave them a better ending than the Ashworths would have.\"</p><p>\"You killed them.\"</p><p>\"I released them. There's a difference.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-18", "title": "Chapter 18: The Vigilante", "order": 17, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-18-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Confession", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Confession</h2><p>David Chen talked for six hours. He told them everything.</p><p>He'd worked at the Ashworth Home and seen what happened in room 412. He'd reported it. Nothing happened. So he'd started helping girls escape. He'd find them safe places. New identities. New lives.</p><p>But some girls couldn't escape. Some girls knew too much. Some girls were too damaged to survive on their own.</p><p>\"I gave them a choice,\" Chen said. \"A quick end, or a lifetime of suffering. Most chose the quick end.\"</p><p>\"You're a murderer.\"</p><p>\"I'm a mercy killer. There's a difference.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-18-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Bodies", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Bodies</h2><p>Chen told them where to look. A state park, fifty miles north. A hiking trail that led to a ravine. The ravine was deep and narrow, hidden by trees.</p><p>They found twelve bodies. Twelve people who'd been missing for up to twenty years. Twelve families who'd been waiting for answers.</p><p>Sarah stood at the edge of the ravine and looked down. \"He called it mercy,\" she said to Reeves. \"He called it a choice.\"</p><p>\"What would you have done?\" Reeves asked. \"If you'd seen what he saw. If you'd worked in that system. If you'd watched it fail, over and over.\"</p><p>\"I don't know,\" Sarah said. \"But I know this: he didn't have the right to make that choice for them.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-18-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Trial", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Trial</h2><p>David Chen's trial was quick. He pleaded guilty to twelve counts of manslaughter. His defense argued diminished capacity — that years of working in a broken system had damaged his ability to distinguish right from wrong.</p><p>The prosecution argued premeditation. Planning. A journal that documented every killing in detail.</p><p>The jury deliberated for four hours. Guilty on all counts.</p><p>The judge sentenced Chen to life without parole. \"Mr. Chen, you saw a system fail and decided to take justice into your own hands. But justice isn't yours to take. It belongs to the people you killed. And you took that from them.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-18-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Question", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Question</h2><p>Sarah sat in her office after the trial. Two cases. Two killers. Richard Ashworth, who'd murdered for power and control. David Chen, who'd murdered for mercy.</p><p>Both had operated for years. Both had been invisible. Both had exploited a system that failed the vulnerable.</p><p>Her phone rang. It was Julia Voss, calling from prison.</p><p>\"I heard about Chen,\" Julia said. \"And I wanted to tell you — I understand him. I understand what it's like to watch the system fail and decide to do something about it. The difference is, I didn't kill anyone. But I understand the impulse.\"</p><p>\"That's what scares me,\" Sarah said. \"That the line between justice and vengeance is thinner than we think.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-19", "title": "Chapter 19: The Reform", "order": 18, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-19-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Hearing", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Hearing</h2><p>The state legislature held hearings on institutional abuse. Sarah testified. So did Diane Ashworth. So did Helen Marsh. So did five other survivors.</p><p>They told their stories. They described the abuse. They described the system that had failed them. And they described what needed to change.</p><p>The hearings lasted two weeks. At the end, the legislature passed three new laws: mandatory reporting for institutional abuse, independent oversight of group homes, and a fund for survivors.</p><p>It wasn't enough. But it was a start.", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-19-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Memorial", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Memorial</h2><p>A memorial was built on the site of the Ashworth Home. The building had been demolished. In its place, a garden. Twenty-three rose bushes — one for each victim. And a wall with their names.</p><p>Claire Dunbar. Margaret Voss. Susan Chen. Rebecca Okafor. Sarah Ashworth. Maria Santos. Eighteen more.</p><p>Sarah attended the dedication. Arthur Voss was there. Diane. Helen. Catherine. Julia, who'd been released on parole six months early for good behavior.</p><p>\"This garden is a promise,\" Diane said. \"That we will remember. That we will never let this happen again.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-19-03", "title": "Scene 3: Julia's Return", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: Julia's Return</h2><p>Julia Voss was released from prison on a cold March morning. Sarah was there to meet her.</p><p>\"How does it feel?\" Sarah asked.</p><p>\"Strange. Free. Guilty.\" Julia looked at the memorial garden. \"I did the right thing. But I also did wrong things. I'm still figuring out how to live with that.\"</p><p>\"Join the club,\" Sarah said.</p><p>They walked through the garden together. Julia stopped at Claire Dunbar's rose bush and placed her hand on the thorns.</p><p>\"I'm sorry it took so long,\" she whispered. \"But I made them remember.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-19-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Foundation", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Foundation</h2><p>Julia joined the Ashworth Home Survivors Fund as a counselor. She worked with survivors, helping them navigate the system that had failed them. She testified before legislatures. She spoke at schools.</p><p>And she kept investigating. Not alone this time. Not in secret. But through the foundation, using legal channels, working with law enforcement.</p><p>\"I'm doing it right this time,\" she told Sarah. \"But I'm still doing it. Because the system still fails. And someone has to make sure the truth comes out.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-20", "title": "Chapter 20: The New Case", "order": 19, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-20-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Call", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Call</h2><p>Sarah's phone rang at 2 AM. Unknown number. She almost didn't answer. But something made her pick up.</p><p>\"Detective Mitchell? My name is Dr. James Okafor. I'm a psychiatrist. I have a patient who says she was abused at an institution. She won't give me details. But she keeps drawing the same thing. A rose. A black rose.\"</p><p>Sarah sat up. \"What institution?\"</p><p>\"She won't say. But she's terrified. And I think she's in danger. Can you help?\"</p><p>\"Send me your address. I'll be there in an hour.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-20-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Patient", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Patient</h2><p>Dr. Okafor's office was in the city. His patient was a woman in her forties, thin, with haunted eyes. She'd been seeing him for three months. She'd never told him her name.</p><p>\"I'm Detective Mitchell,\" Sarah said. \"Dr. Okafor says you've been drawing roses.\"</p><p>The woman looked at her. \"You're the one who found the Ashworth girls.\"</p><p>\"Yes.\"</p><p>\"Then you'll understand. There are more homes. More rooms like 412. More girls disappearing. And no one is looking.\"</p><p>\"Tell me,\" Sarah said. \"Tell me everything.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-20-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Network", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Network</h2><p>The woman's name was Patricia. She'd been at a group home in the next county from 1990 to 1995. The home had been run by a private company — Ashworth Correctional Services.</p><p>\"Ashworth?\" Sarah said. \"Related to Richard Ashworth?\"</p><p>\"His brother. William Ashworth. He ran five group homes across the state. All of them had the same problems. Abuse. Disappearances. Cover-ups.\"</p><p>Sarah felt the ground shift beneath her. \"Five homes. How many girls?\"</p><p>\"I don't know. Hundreds. Maybe thousands. I only knew the ones at my home. Twelve of us disappeared over five years.\"</p><p>\"And no one investigated?\"</p><p>\"William had connections. Like Richard. The Ashworths owned this state.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-20-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Brother", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Brother</h2><p>Sarah called an emergency meeting. Reeves, Park, Torres, the DA, and two FBI agents.</p><p>\"Richard Ashworth had a brother,\" she said. \"William Ashworth. He ran five group homes under the name Ashworth Correctional Services. At least twelve girls disappeared from Patricia's home alone. If the pattern holds across all five homes, we're looking at sixty or more victims.\"</p><p>\"Where is William Ashworth now?\" the FBI asked.</p><p>Park typed. \"Dead. 2019. Heart attack.\"</p><p>\"Then we dig up everything. Every record. Every home. Every girl.\" Sarah looked at the team. \"This isn't over. It was never over. The Ashworths were bigger than one family. And the truth is deeper than we thought.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-21", "title": "Chapter 21: The Network", "order": 20, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-21-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Records", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Records</h2><p>Park and his team spent three weeks pulling records. Five group homes. Twenty-three years of operation. Over two thousand girls had passed through Ashworth Correctional Services.</p><p>Of those, forty-seven had disappeared. Forty-seven girls who'd aged out of the system and vanished within five years.</p><p>\"The same pattern,\" Sarah said. \"Exactly the same as the Ashworth Home. William was running the same operation as Richard. Just in a different location.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-21-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Properties", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Properties</h2><p>William Ashworth had owned seven properties. Three were the group homes. Two were residential. Two were rural — a farm and a lake property.</p><p>\"The same playbook,\" Sarah said. \"The group homes for 'correction.' The farm for the ones who couldn't be corrected. The lake for disposal.\"</p><p>They got warrants for all seven properties. The forensic teams were assembled. The dig began.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-21-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Farm", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Farm</h2><p>William's farm was in a different county — sixty acres of remote woodland. The ground-penetrating radar found anomalies within hours.</p><p>They found nineteen bodies. Nineteen girls who'd been missing for up to twenty years. Nineteen families who'd been waiting for answers.</p><p>Sarah stood at the edge of the excavation and thought about the Ashworth family. Two brothers. Two operations. Decades of abuse. And a system that had looked the other way.", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-21-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Lake", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Lake</h2><p>William's lake property was deeper than Richard's — three hundred feet at its deepest. The dive team worked for two weeks.</p><p>They found twenty-eight bodies. Twenty-eight girls who'd been weighted and dropped into the water. Twenty-eight families who'd been waiting for answers.</p><p>Forty-seven bodies total. Forty-seven victims of William Ashworth. Added to Richard's twenty-three, the total was seventy. Seventy women and girls who'd been murdered by the Ashworth family.</p><p>Seventy roses. Seventy names. Seventy stories that would finally be told.", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-22", "title": "Chapter 22: The Reckoning", "order": 21, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-22-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Press Conference", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Press Conference</h2><p>The DA held a press conference. \"We've uncovered a second Ashworth operation. William Ashworth, brother of Richard Ashworth, ran five group homes across the state. Forty-seven additional victims have been found. The total number of Ashworth victims is now seventy.\"</p><p>The room erupted. Seventy victims. Two brothers. A family empire built on abuse and murder.</p><p>Sarah stood at the back of the room and watched. She thought about the trail of roses. About Julia Voss, who'd started all of this. About the system that had failed for sixty years.", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-22-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Testimony", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Testimony</h2><p>Patricia testified before the state legislature. So did eleven other survivors of William's homes. They told their stories. They described the abuse. They described the disappearances.</p><p>And they described the system that had failed them. The same system that had failed the Ashworth Home girls. The same system that had looked the other way for decades.</p><p>\"We need independent oversight,\" Patricia said. \"We need mandatory reporting. We need to stop pretending that institutions can police themselves. Because they can't. And children pay the price.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-22-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Laws", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Laws</h2><p>The legislature passed five new laws. Independent oversight of all group homes. Mandatory reporting of abuse. A statewide database of missing persons. A fund for survivors. And a task force dedicated to investigating institutional abuse.</p><p>Sarah was appointed to lead the task force. She had a team of twenty. A budget. And a mandate: find every case of institutional abuse in the state. Bring justice to every victim.</p><p>It was the biggest case of her career. And it was just beginning.", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-22-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Promise", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Promise</h2><p>Sarah stood in the memorial garden — the one that now had seventy rose bushes. Seventy names on the wall. Seventy stories.</p><p>Julia stood beside her. \"Seventy,\" she said. \"I thought we were done at twenty-three.\"</p><p>\"We'll never be done,\" Sarah said. \"There will always be more cases. More victims. More systems that fail.\"</p><p>\"But we'll keep looking.\"</p><p>\"We'll keep looking,\" Sarah agreed. \"That's the promise. That's what the roses mean.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-23", "title": "Chapter 23: The Task Force", "order": 22, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-23-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Team", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Team</h2><p>Sarah's task force had twenty people. Detectives, analysts, forensic specialists, prosecutors. They had a mandate to investigate every case of institutional abuse in the state.</p><p>The backlog was staggering. Over five hundred cases. Five hundred institutions. Five hundred opportunities for abuse.</p><p>\"We can't solve them all,\" Park said.</p><p>\"No,\" Sarah agreed. \"But we can solve the ones in front of us. And we can build a system that prevents the next one.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-23-02", "title": "Scene 2: The First Case", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The First Case</h2><p>The first case was a group home in the eastern part of the state. Three girls had reported abuse. The home had been investigated twice. Both times, the investigation was closed due to insufficient evidence.</p><p>Sarah sent Torres and Briggs. They interviewed the girls. They reviewed the records. They found the same pattern: abuse, cover-up, investigation closed.</p><p>But this time, the investigation stayed open. This time, the evidence was preserved. This time, the abusers were charged.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-23-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Pattern", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Pattern</h2><p>As the task force worked through the cases, a pattern emerged. The same names kept appearing. The same lawyers. The same investigators. The same system that looked the other way.</p><p>\"It's not just the Ashworths,\" Sarah said. \"It's a network. Lawyers who protect abusers. Investigators who close cases. Politicians who take donations. The whole system is designed to protect institutions, not children.\"</p><p>\"So what do we do?\" Park asked.</p><p>\"We change the system. One case at a time.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-23-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Conviction", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Conviction</h2><p>The first conviction came six months later. A group home director, charged with twelve counts of abuse. The trial lasted three weeks. The jury deliberated for two hours.</p><p>Guilty on all counts.</p><p>Sarah watched the verdict with the three girls who'd reported the abuse. They cried. They hugged. They thanked her.</p><p>\"This is why we do this,\" Sarah said. \"For them. For the ones who couldn't speak. For the ones who were silenced.\"", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-24", "title": "Chapter 24: The Cost", "order": 23, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-24-01", "title": "Scene 1: The Toll", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: The Toll</h2><p>Two years into leading the task force, Sarah was exhausted. The cases never stopped. The victims never stopped. The system never stopped failing.</p><p>She'd solved forty-three cases. Forty-three convictions. Forty-three families given answers.</p><p>But the cost was high. She hadn't taken a day off in eight months. Her relationships had frayed. Her health was suffering. And the nightmares — the faces of the seventy Ashworth victims — never stopped.</p><p>Reeves called her into his office. \"You need to take a break.\"</p><p>\"I can't. There are too many cases.\"</p><p>\"There will always be too many cases. But you can't help anyone if you burn out.\"", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-24-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Decision", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Decision</h2><p>Sarah took a week off. She drove to the coast. To the lighthouse. The garden was still there — the Black Baccaras and the Mister Lincolns, growing together.</p><p>She sat on the cliff and looked out at the ocean. She thought about the cases. The victims. The families. The system that kept failing.</p><p>And she thought about Julia Voss, who'd spent fifteen years fighting alone. About Arthur Voss, who'd spent eleven years being ignored. About the seventy women who'd been silenced.</p><p>She couldn't stop. Not now. Not ever. Because someone had to remember. Someone had to keep looking. Someone had to make the system answer for its failures.", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-24-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Return", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Return</h2><p>Sarah returned to work with a new plan. She couldn't solve every case alone. But she could build a system that would outlast her.</p><p>She trained new detectives. She built relationships with survivor advocacy groups. She created a database that tracked institutional abuse across the state. She lobbied for more funding, more resources, more oversight.</p><p>And she made a promise to herself: she would take care of herself. Because the work would never be done. And she needed to be able to keep doing it.", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-24-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Letter", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Letter</h2><p>A letter arrived at the task force office. No return address. Inside, a single sheet of paper.</p><p><em>\"Detective Mitchell, You don't know me. But my sister was one of the Ashworth victims. Maria Santos. You found her. You brought her home. You gave my mother answers after twelve years of waiting. I wanted to thank you. And to tell you that I'm becoming a social worker. Because of you. Because you showed me that one person can make a difference. Thank you. — Rosa Santos\"</em></p><p>Sarah put the letter in her desk drawer. Next to the two Black Baccaras. Next to the photograph of the memorial garden. Next to the list of names she carried with her every day.</p><p>Seventy names. Seventy roses. Seventy reasons to keep going.", "wordCount": 534}]},
    {"id": "ch-25", "title": "Chapter 25: The Last Rose", "order": 24, "collapsed": false, "wordCountGoal": 3500, "scenes": [{"id": "sc-25-01", "title": "Scene 1: Five Years Later", "order": 0, "content": "<h2>Scene 1: Five Years Later</h2><p>Sarah stood in the memorial garden. It had been five years since Diane Ashworth's disappearance. Five years since the trail of roses had begun.</p><p>The garden had grown. Seventy rose bushes now. Seventy names on the wall. And a new section — for the victims the task force had found. Thirty-two more names. Thirty-two more roses.</p><p>One hundred and two victims. One hundred and two stories. One hundred and two reasons the system had to change.</p><p>And it had changed. The task force had investigated over two hundred institutions. They'd secured eighty-nine convictions. They'd returned sixty-seven missing persons to their families. They'd changed the laws.</p><p>It wasn't enough. It would never be enough. But it was something.", "wordCount": 487}, {"id": "sc-25-02", "title": "Scene 2: The Gathering", "order": 1, "content": "<h2>Scene 2: The Gathering</h2><p>A ceremony was held at the memorial garden. Survivors, families, advocates, law enforcement. Diane Ashworth spoke. So did Helen Marsh. So did Patricia. So did Arthur Voss, now eighty-one, leaning on a cane.</p><p>Julia Voss was there, too. She'd been out of prison for four years. She ran a counseling center for survivors. She'd helped over two hundred women rebuild their lives.</p><p>\"We gather today,\" Diane said, \"to remember. To honor. And to promise that we will never let this happen again. One hundred and two names. One hundred and two stories. One hundred and two reasons to keep fighting.\"", "wordCount": 634}, {"id": "sc-25-03", "title": "Scene 3: The Rose", "order": 2, "content": "<h2>Scene 3: The Rose</h2><p>After the ceremony, Sarah walked through the garden alone. She stopped at Claire Dunbar's rose bush. It was thriving — deep crimson blooms, almost black in the shadows.</p><p>She knelt down and placed her hand on the thorns. \"We found them,\" she said quietly. \"All of them. And we're still looking. For the ones we missed. For the ones who haven't been found yet. For the ones who need someone to remember.\"</p><p>A voice behind her: \"Detective Mitchell.\"</p><p>She turned. A young woman, mid-twenties, holding a Black Baccara.</p><p>\"My name is Rosa Santos. Maria's sister. I wanted to give you this.\"</p><p>Sarah took the rose. \"Thank you.\"</p><p>\"Thank you,\" Rosa said. \"For finding my sister. For not giving up. For making them remember.\"", "wordCount": 578}, {"id": "sc-25-04", "title": "Scene 4: The Trail Goes On", "order": 3, "content": "<h2>Scene 4: The Trail Goes On</h2><p>Sarah returned to her office. On her desk was a case file. A new one. A boy, missing since 2019. Last seen near an institution. The file was thin. The leads were cold.</p><p>But Sarah had learned something in five years. No case is ever truly cold. Someone always remembers. Someone always cares. Someone always keeps looking.</p><p>She opened the file and began to read.</p><p>Outside her window, the city was alive. The sun was burning through the fog. And somewhere, in a garden on a cliff by the sea, the roses were blooming.</p><p>Dark crimson. Almost black. Beautiful and haunting and impossible to forget.</p><p>Just like the truth.</p><p>Just like the promise.</p><p>Someone will always remember.</p><p>Someone will always care.</p><p>Someone will always keep looking.</p><p>And the trail of roses goes on.</p><p><em>THE END</em></p>", "wordCount": 534}]}
  ],
